class SeatManager {
public:
    SeatManager(int n) {
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            available_seats.push(i);
        }
    }

    int reserve() {
        int smallest_seat = available_seats.top();
        available_seats.pop();
        return smallest_seat;
    }

    void unreserve(int seatNumber) {
        available_seats.push(seatNumber);
    }
private:
    std::priority_queue<int, std::vector<int>, std::greater<int>> available_seats;
};
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: 
- `SeatManager(int n)`: O(n)
- `reserve()`: O(log n)
- `unreserve(int seatNumber)`: O(log n)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The `SeatManager` class utilizes a min-heap (implemented as a priority queue in C++) to efficiently manage the available seats. The constructor initializes the min-heap with all seat numbers from 1 to n. The `reserve` method retrieves the smallest available seat by popping the top element from the min-heap, while the `unreserve` method adds the seat back into the min-heap, allowing it to be considered for future reservations. This approach ensures that the smallest available seat is always reserved first.

